<p class="">I am much obliged to you for your protection, Mr. Deputy-Speaker. Might I ask your view, having regard to the fact that you have ruled that what has been put is neither tedious repetition nor irrelevant, whether the Chair is now seeking to assert a right to prescribe the length to which hon. Members may go in their arguments which are admitted to be relevant and which are admitted not to be tedious repetition? May I ask, with due submission, whether there is any precedent whatever in the history of this House for the Chair asserting such a right?</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
